{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_fleur_ver01/data/sn83035189/00516993777/1937120201/0667.xml":{"full_text":"BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nSTATE AND NATION\n_\n\nAverage Ohio Farmer Has\nBetter Position Than\nProducers Elsewhere\nIn adapting government business\noutiook reports to Ohio farm condi\ntions, members of the Ohio State Uni\nversity rurai economics department\nsay, \"The average Ohio farmer is in\na better economic position than the\naverage United States farmer for the\nnext 12 months. The Ohio farmer\nhas a relatively large supply of live\nstock and also has a fairly large feed\nsupply.\n\"The 1934 and 1936 drouths forced\nconsiderable liquidation of livestock\nin the drouth areas; and from\nJanuary 1, 1934 to January 1, 1937,\nthe number of cattle and calves in the\nUnited States declined 11 per cent\nbut there was a decrease of only two\npeT cent in the numbers of cattle and\ncalves in Ohio. Farmers in the whole\nnation reduced the numbers of milk\ncows by seven per cent but the num\nbers decreased only two per cent in\nOhio; and the number of hogs on\nfarms in Ohio declined only 11.6 per\ncent while the decline was 27 per cent\nfor the country as a whole.\n\"The presence of the fairly large\nnumbers of livestock in Ohio and the\nprospects for continuing good prices\nmake the Ohio farmers' position rel\natively secure for the coming year.\nCrop production was good in the\nstate in 1937 and farmers have a\nlarge supply of feeds to market\nthrough their livestock.\"\nNational economic authorities say,\n\"The demand for farm products\nprobably will not be as favorable in\n1938 as it was in 1937. This outlook\nis based upon an analysis of the gen\neral situation, which indicates that\nthe upswing of the business cycle has\nbeen temporarily halted in the fall\nof 1937.\n\"Increased supplies of farm prod\nucts in the United States and de\ncreased supplies available in foreign\ncountries should result in a material\nly larger volume of agricultural ex\nports from this country in 1938.\nBoth buying prices and buying power\nper unit of farm products are ex\npected to be lower in 1938. The total\nnational income for 1938 is expected\nto be below the high level of $69,000,\n000,000 which prevailed in 1937.\n\"Some slackening in the rate of\nautomobile production in 1938 as com\npared with 1937 may occur. A large\npotential demand for steel products\nfrom the railroads is indicated by the\ncapacity and condition of existing\nequipment and roadbed in relation to\nprospective traffic needs but this de\nmand will become effective only as\nthe volume of trafhc and net earn\nings make practicable the financing\nof replacements and improvements.\n\"Building activity experiences cycli\ncal swings which seem to be of long\ner duration than the business cycle.\nThe bottom of the present construc\ntion cycle apparently was reached in\n1932-34, and an irregular advance is\nexpected for several years. In 1938,\nthe total volume of construction is ex\npected to be slightly greater than in\n1937.\n\"Many of the conditions which in\nthe past have been associated with\nthe ending of a major upswing in\nbusiness activity are absent now.\nBusiness debts are low, credit ia\ncheap and plentiful, banking resources\nare not attained, there is no building\nboom, and there has been an absence\nof violent speculation of the type\nwhich usually precedes the end of a\nbusiness boom.\n'There also are a numoer 01 un\nfavorable indications in the general\nsituation. The stimulus for risea in\nbusiness activity at various times\nsince 1933 has come, to a very con\nsiderable extent, from government\nspending, deficit financing, and mon\netary measures. The bonus distribu\ntion in 1936 undoubtedly proved to be\na material stimulus to business in\n1936. With the tendency to curtail\ngovernment spending and the expan\nsion of credit by deficit financing\nthrough banks, such stimuli are like\nly to play a less prominent part in\nbusiness advances during the next\nfew years.\n\"The level of wholesale prices in\nthe United States is expected to be\nlower in 1938 than in 1937, with pro\nspective lower prices for raw ma\nterials, farm products, and some kinds\nof manufactured goods more than\noffsetting higher prices for some\nlines of finished and semi-finished\nproducts. Retail prices probably\nhave not yet reflected all the rise in\nwholesale prices of manufactured\nproducts and in marketing costs.\n\"Indications point to some further\nincreases in retail prices of furni\nture, furnishings, shoes, and fuel.\nThe effect on living costs of these in\ncrease probably will be oyset in part\nby lower prices of rayon and cotton\nclothing, meats, and some other foods.\nThe rise in rents is expected ^con\ntinue but perhaps at a lower rate.\n\"The genera! trend of prices for\nfarm products has been downward\nsince January, 1937; and in September\nthe index number of farm prices was\n118 compared with 124 in September,\n1936.! Farm prices are expected to\naverage lower in 1938 than in 1937.\nPrices paid by farmers in September\nwere about 130 per cent of pre-war\nand three points higher than a year\nwriter. Some further advance in\nprices paid by farmers may occur in\n938 so that the buying power of farm\nncome ia not expected to be as high\nt. in 1937.\"\nWoman's Exchange Hold\nOpening Sale On Saurday\nSaturday, December 4 marks the\nopening sale of the Woman's Ex*\n:hange organized by Mrs. Vioiet\nMoore. Subscribers can dispose of\nhome made sewing, art needlework,\npastries, candies, etc. The location\nat present is in a part of the West\nUnion Bowiing Alley, south of the\ncourt house on Cross street. The\npublic is cordially invited.\nHUGE SUif NEEDED\nTO RUN THE STATE\nFour Organizations Protest\nChanging Law On Special\nRelief Tax Levies\nColumbus, Ohio:\u2014 Supplemental\nappropriations totaiing $2,831,333 for\nvarious state departments and insti\ntutions Wednesday were asked of\nthe legislature by Governor Martin L.\nDavey for the remainder of this year\nand next.\nEducational institutions led the list\nwith a total of $1,197,137, of which\nKent State University would receive\n$735,000. Of the Kent State Univer\nsity allotment, $650,000 would be used\nto construct a new science building.\nOhio State University would re\nceive $226,840; Ohio University, $74,\n000; Miami, $42,000; Bowling Green,\n$40,000; Wiiberforce, $30,000, and tne\nOhio Soldiers' and Sailors' Orphans'\nHome, $4,500.\nOther items inciude $260,923 for\nthe state tax commission; $78,445 for\nthe utilities commission; $160,570 for\nthe state highway patrol; $323,560 for\nthe welfare department; $250,000 for\nthe emergency board, and $90,000 for\nthe Ohio National Guard.\nLake White, in Pike county, also'\nwould he allotted an additional $6,000\nfor wages and an automobile,\nfor the parole board.\nOf the welfare department's allot\nment $84,000 is for food and $42,000\nMeanwhile four powerful organiza\ntions representing real estate own\ners entered vigorous protests against\nproposals to reduce the present 65\nper cent favorable vote required for\nspecial tax levies for relief.\nThe Ohio Farm Bureau, Ohio As\nsociation of Real Estate Boards, the\nCleveland Apartment House Owners\nAssociation and the Cuyahoga County\nTax League lined up before the\nHouse taxation committee against\nproposals to reduce the vote require\nment to a bare majority.\nRepresentatives of those associa\ntions asserted that the organizations\nwold support tax levies for relief and\nstatutory welfare purposes if the!\namounts sought were reasonable, thus j\nmaking it possible to pass such levies\nby a 65 per cent favorable vote.\nL. F. Efferth, representing the\ntwo Cleveland associations, said they\nwould support an extra tax levy of\n2.3 mills for statutory welfare in\nCuyahoga county. They opposed\npassage of a 2.8 mills levy, which was\ndefeated at the recent election.\nMr. Efferth did not indicate wheth\ner the associations would oppose\nlowering from 65 per cent to a bare\nmajority the vote necessary for\nemergency relief levies. The eom\nmitee yesterday considered only bills\naffecting statutory welfare.\nJ. M. Hodson, representing the\nfarm bureau and Ivan H. Gore, rep\nresenting the Ohio Association of\nReal Estate Boards, said their objec\ntion to any change in the present 65\nper cent requirement extends both to\nlevies for emergency relief and sta\ntutory welfare.\nNEW BELL'S THEATER\nHILLSBORO. OHIO\nFRIDAY AND SATURDAY\nDecember 3 and 4\nGENE AUTRY in\n\"PUBLIC ENEMY NO. 1\"\n\u2014ALSO\u2014\nLew Ayres and Mary Carlisle in\n\"HOLD 'EM NAVY\"\nSUNDAY. MONDAY.TUESDAY\nDecember5, 6 and 7\nBert Wheeler, Robt. Woolsey and\nLnpe Velez in\n\"HIGH FLYERS\"\n\u2014EXTRA\u2014\nHa! LeRoy in Two-Reel Comedy\nWEDNESDAY AND THURSDAY\nDecember 8 and 9\n\"LOVE IS ON THE AIR\"\nWith an All-Star Cast\nEvery Thursday is Movie Sweep\nstakes. You may be the next winner.\n(270.00\u2014DECEMBER 2\u2014(270.00\n\u2014AT LAST\u2014\nSUNDAY, MONDAY, TUESDAY,\nWEDNESDAY\nDecember 12, 13, 14 and 15\nFred Astaire, Burns Allen in\nA DAMSEL IN DISTRESS'\nDATES SET FOR\nFARM MEETS\n(Continued from page one)\n\"Preparing for Life\"\u2014-Charles W.\nPeters.\nSong by audience.\nDinner to be served at a small cost\nby the Liberty township P.-T. A.\nAfternoon Session\n1:16\u2014Song by audience.\nSpecial music by school.\n\"Housekeeping or Home Making?\"\n\u2014Mrs. McConnell.\nDiscussion.\nMusic\u2014Oliver Haas family.\nSong by school.\n\"Amerida's Major Problem\"\u2014Mr.\nPeters.\nDiscussion.\nSong by the group.\nEvening Session\n7:15\u2014Music by Liberty band, in\ncharge of Ray Shell.\n7:30\u2014\"What's the Hurry?\" (Tak\ning time to enjoy real living)\u2014Mrs.\nMcConnell.\nSpecial music\u2014Richard Patton.\nSong\u2014Liberty-Tifhn quartette.\n\"That Eternal Quest for Happi\nness^\u2014Mr. Peters.\nClosing song by audience.\nMusic\u2014Liberty band.\nDevotional\u2014Rev. C. P. Wedgewood.\nMorning Session, December 9\n10\u2014Song by audience.\nInvocation\u2014Rev. Wm. A. Boehnker.\n\"Growing with Their Years\"\u2014Mrs.\nMcConnell.\nGroup singing by audience.\nMonologue\u2014Charles Foster.\n\"Developing a Profitable Side Line\"\nMr. Peters.\nDiscussion.\nDinner to be served at a smati cost\nby the Liberty township P.-T. A.\nAfternoon Session\n1:16\u2014Song by audience\n\"Educated\u2014When and Why?\"\u2014\nMrs. McConnell.\nReading\u2014-Mrs. Edna Moore.\nGrange p!ay by Jerusalem Grange,\nin charge of Corrine Foster.\n\"Why Religious Education\"\u2014Mr.\nPeters.\nDevotions!\u2014Rev. W. E. Mills.\nEvening Session\n7:15\u2014Music by string orchestra, in\ncharge of Harry Shipley.\nPiay by Equity Union ofHcials, in\ncharge of Karl Pierce.\nA collection will be taken after this\nsession to pay for the Independent\nFarmers' Institute for next year.\nBring a nickel or a dime extra and\ncontribute.\nProgram for the Wheat Ridge\nState Aid Farmers' Institute to be\nheld in the Wheat Ridge Grange hall\non Friday, December 10 and Saturday,\nDecember 11:\nMorning Session, December 10\n10\u2014'Song by audience.\nInvocation\u2014Rev. E. M. Duffey.\n\"Lessons from Nature\"\u2014Mrs. D. R.\nMcConnell.\nExercises by Olive school, in charge\nof Mrs. Efhe Newman.\nExercises by Harshaville school, in\ncharge of Raymond Hayslip.\n\"Preparing for Life\"\u2014Charles W.\nPeters.\nExercises by Rhoades school, in\ncharge of Mrs. Henrietta Wills.\nBasket dinner Everybody bring\ndinner and eat together.\nAfternoon Session\n1:15\u2014Song by audience.\n\"Housekeeping or Home Making?\"\n\u2014Mrs. McConnell.\nExercises by Dunkinsville school, in\ncharge of Mrs. Ethel Simmons.\n\"Developing a Profitable Side Line\"\nMr. Peters.\nExercises by Unity school, in\ncharge of Mrs. Marjorie Young.\nEvening Session\n7:15\u2014'Music by Swearingen's or\nchestra.\n7:30\u2014\"Our National Dangers are\nWithin\"\u2014Mrs. McConnell.\nPlay by Wheat Ridge Grange.\nMusic\u2014Swearingen's orchestra.\n\"That Eternal Quest for Happi\nness\"\u2014Mr. Peters.\n(Jtosing song oy audrence.\nDevotionai\u2014Rev. Strickland.\nMorning Session, December 11\n10\u2014Song by audience.\nInvocation\u2014Rev. Paul McLaughlin.\n\"Educated \u2014When and Why\nMrs. D. R. McConneii.\nGroup singing.\n\"Changing Our Government\"\u2014Mr.\nPeters.\nSong by Grange quartette, in\ncharge of C. H. Campbeii.\nBasket dinner\u2014Everyibody bring\ndinner and eat together.\nAfternoon Session\n1:15\u2014Song by audience.\n\"What's the Hurry\" Mrs. Mc\nConnell.\nSong by Grange quartette, in\ncharge of C. H. Campbell.\nGroup singing.\n\"America's Major Problem\"\u2014Mr.\nPeters.\nPlans are being made to hold a\nMiniature Fair. A11 folks are urged\nto bring farm, garden, and fancy\nwork, and make a nice display. There\nwill be small awards go to the best\nof each. See your officers- about this.\nW. E. Browning, is president, J. F.\nBissinger, vice president; M. Elma\nFrush, secretary, and Della Campbell,\nhostess.\nProgram for the Blue Creek State\nAid Farmers' Institute to be held at\nMoore's Chape! in Jefferson township\non Monday, December 13 and Tues\nday, December 14:\nMorning Session, December 13\nId\u2014Invocation by Rev. Sara Bow\nman.\nRemarks\u2014Supt. Leonard Day.\nSUNDAY, MONDAY, TUESDAY,\nWEDNESDAY\nDecember 12 13, 14 end 15\nFred Astaire, Bums Aden in\n\"A DAMSEL !N\nD!STRESS\"\nAt BELL'S THEATRE\nHillsboro, Ohio\nSong by audience.\n\"Why Live in the Country?\"\u2014Mrs.\nD. R. McConneii.\nSong by Girls Glee Club, in charge\nof Miss Edna Shuster.\n\"Preparing for Life\"\u2014Charles W.\nPeters.\nSong.\nAdjourn for dinner, to be served by\nHome Ec. class at small cost.\nAfternoon Session\n1:15\u2014Song by audience.\n\"Housekeeping or Home Making?\"\n\u2014Mrs. McConnell.\nSong by Boys Glee Club, in charge\nof Miss Edna Shuster.\n\"Changing Our Government\"\u2014Mr.\nPeters.\nSong by audience.\nEvening Session\n7:15\u2014Music by school band, in\ncharge of Roy Liston.\n7:30\u2014Song by audience.\n\"Our National Dangers are With\nin\"\u2014Mrs. McConnell.\nSong by audience.\nPlay by Blue Creek Grange.\n\"That Eternal Quest for Happi\nness\"\u2014Mrs. Peters.\nMusic by band.\nClosing song.\nDevotional\u2014Rev. Wilbur Stivers.\nMorning Session, December 14\n10\u2014Song by audience.\nInvocation.\n\"Educated When and w hy 7\nMrs. McConnell.\nDiscussion.\nMusic Jefferson Township high\nschool.\nSong by audience.\n\"Developing a Profitabie Side Line\"\n\u2014Mr. Peters.\nDiscussion.\nAdjourn for dinner, bring basket\ndinner and eat together.\nAfternoon Session\n1:15\u2014Song by audience.\n\"Your Community\"\u2014Mrs. McCon\nnell.\nMusic by school.\n\"The Use of Fertilizer in a Per\nmanent Agriculture\"\u2014Mr. Peters.\nClosing song.\nOfHcers for this institute are: Pres\nident, W. P. Newman; Vice President,\nIke Copas; Secretary, Earl Brown;\nHostess, Mrs. Edith Hafer.\nObituary\n\nAgain the Death Angel has visited\nour community taking from us Mary\nE. Bell, daughter of Philip and Sarah\nJ. Hardin. She was bom near Tran\nquillity on February 3, 1880 and de\nparted this life October 11, 1937 at\nher home near Winchester, being 57\nyears, 8 months and 8 days of age.\nShe was united in marriage to\nSamuel T. Bell on October 10, 1899\nand for more than thirty-eight years\nthey have journeyed down life's\npathway sharing the joys and sor\nrows of life together. To this union\nthree children were bom to gladen\ntheir hearts and home.\nOn January 23, 1919 this home was\nsaddened by the hand of death tak\ning their oldest daughter Minnie\nEdna, leaving the other two, namely:\nMrs. Melvin Thomas of Seaman,\nOhio, and Roy Bell at home. She\nleaves two grandchildren, Samuel\nRaymond and Mary Lou Thomas.\nOne grandchild Barbara Ann Bel! pre\nceded her in death. She leaves four\nbrothers and three sisters: Hiram\nHardin, Alfred Hardin, Hobart Hard\nin of Seaman, Ohio, John Hardin of\nCincinnati, Ohio, Blanche Edendeld,\nRuth Howard of Seaman, Ohio, and\nAnna Post of Hillsboro, Ohio, and\nmany relatives and friends.\nMe gave ner neart to t*oa ana net\nhand to the Methodist church of Sea\nman, Ohio in eariy womanhood, but\nin later years transferred her mem\nbership to the Fiat Run M. E. church\nand remained a member of that\nchurch until the time of her death.\nOur hearts are sad and ionely,\nA voice we ioved is stilled;\nA place is vacant in our home,\nWhich never can be hlled.\nDear mother, thou art gone,\nThy toils and sufferings are o'er;\nGod in His wisdom saw it best,\nTo call thee to the other shore.\nWith sorrowing hearts we give thee\nnp,\nTo sleep beneath the sod;\nBut we must drink the bitter cup,\nAnd put our trust in God.\nHelp us, O Lord, to trust in Thee,\nAnd that heavenly home to gain;\nWhere we may meet and with loved\nones be,\nWith Thee forever remain.\nCard of Thanks\nWe wish to extend our most sincere\nthanks to our neighbors and friends\nfor their kindness shown us during\nthe illness and death of our wife and\nmother. Also to the donors of the\nbeautiful flowers, to the singers, and\nto Rev. Russell Bowman for his con\nsoling words, and to Lewis and Son,\nthe undertakers for their efficient\nservice.\nHusband ami children.\nFarmers can not obtain any govern\nment payments to permit inoculation\nof hogs to prevent choiera nor as re\nimbursement for hogs which have\nbeen victims of that disease.\nCALDWELL'S\nBARGAIN BASEMENT!\nLocated in B. L. Building\nCHARLEY STOUT, Manager WEST UNION, OHIO\nJUST ARRIVED?\nWomen's New\nPURSES\nActual $1.19 vaiues. Clever\nstyles and shapes, In suedes or\nleathers. Plenty of zipper styles\ntoo. Now for only\u2014\n97c\nWOMEN'S 59c BRUSHED\nWOOL GLOVES\nBright new plaid combina\ntions. First quality\u2014while they\nlast\u2014\n49c\nWOMEN'S\nParis Fashion and\nStar Brand\nSTYLE SHOES\nAll sizes and widths in new\nmulti-color suedes and plain\ncolors. Several outstanding\nstyles to pick from. Extra spe\ncial\u2014\n$2.91\nMEN'S OR BOYS'\nBlanket Lined\nOVERALL JACKETS\nAetna! (1.59 value. Full cut\